rawContent:
I see the main advantage of projects like Oxya, PA, Roos or PGodjira in the fact that they kept building during the bear without pumping the floor.

Question to ask is, what did it do to the community?

All the doubters have left, strong core remained. People who understand the vision, people who have a reason to hold, support and work alongside the team.

What will happen when their product becomes successful? Holders will hold, or perhaps take partial profits, new holders will come in. The old community will take care of them. The OG community will be experienced, will know ins and outs of the project and solidify the new holders into the community.

That‚Äôs why I like these undervalued gems.

I really don‚Äôt understand why would anyone buy a 4 or 10 ETH NFT after the team has pumped them to oblivion without sharing their revenue/business model and how the holders will participate in that. Well, that‚Äôs their problem.

The key to making it in NFTs is to identify these undervalued gems sub 0.5 or even better sub 0.2 ETH who have been building their products & community during the bear and who have a clear value proposition for the holder community. There‚Äôs not many of them. But Oxya does count into this group, in my opinion.
